President Donald J. Trump has declared a state of emergency in Michigan due to severe storms and flooding that began on May 16, 2020. The declaration authorizes the Department of Homeland Security and the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) to coordinate relief efforts and provide assistance to alleviate the hardship caused by the emergency. FEMA is authorized to mobilize resources and equipment to mitigate the impacts of the emergency. The federal funding for emergency protective measures will be provided at 75 percent. James K. Joseph has been named the Federal Coordinating Officer for recovery operations in the affected areas. For more information, media can contact the FEMA News Desk.